## Comparative Overview of Party Systems in U.S. History

| Era                     | Dominant Parties              | Key Characteristics                                     | Major Developments                               |
|-------------------------|------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------|
| First Party System (1792–1824) | Federalists vs. Democratic-Republicans | Emergence of organized parties; debates over federal power | Federalists decline; Era of Good Feelings        |
| Second Party System (1828–1860) | Democrats vs. Whigs           | Increased voter participation; party machines           | Rise of Democratic Party; Whig opposition        |
| Civil War Era (1850s–1860s) | Democrats vs. Republicans      | Slavery issue divides parties; Republican rise           | Republican Party founded; dominance of two parties |
| New Deal Era (1930s–1960s) | Democrats vs. Republicans      | Broad New Deal coalition; expanded government role       | Strengthened party organizations                  |
| Modern Era (1960s–Present) | Democrats vs. Republicans      | Candidate-centered politics; ideological polarization    | Party realignments; increased party strength      |

